00:19:03,367 --> 00:19:05,202
Are you all right?

263
00:19:05,869 --> 00:19:07,204
Are you all right?

264
00:19:09,081 --> 00:19:10,082
Thank you, God.

265
00:19:12,292 --> 00:19:13,292
<i>(DOOR OPENS)</i>

266
00:19:13,293 --> 00:19:14,293
Come on. Get up.

267
00:19:14,461 --> 00:19:16,088
- I said, get up!
- Eliza: No, don't...

268
00:19:16,213 --> 00:19:18,173
I don't want to
hear you talk! Get in the yard.

269
00:19:18,298 --> 00:19:19,298
Not my children!

270
00:19:19,383 --> 00:19:22,845
Ain't no need for all that.
Just taking a little trip, that's all.

271
00:19:23,387 --> 00:19:25,097
Don't want to
frighten the children

272
00:19:25,180 --> 00:19:26,849
over a little
boat ride, do you?

273
00:19:27,015 --> 00:19:28,767
John's master
gonna pay his debt.

274
00:19:28,851 --> 00:19:29,852
Line up!

275
00:19:30,018 --> 00:19:31,178
His master gonna
pay his debt!

276
00:19:31,186 --> 00:19:32,855
<i>(JOHN GROANING)</i>

277
00:19:37,025 --> 00:19:39,778
I don't want to hear a word
out of none of you!

278
00:19:40,779 --> 00:19:42,030
Not a one.

279
00:19:55,169 --> 00:19:56,545
BURCH: All right, come on.

280
00:19:58,172 --> 00:20:00,048
- Move.
- Come on.

281
00:20:01,508 --> 00:20:03,093
Come on, child.
Come on.

282
00:20:03,218 --> 00:20:04,845
Follow your mama.

283
00:20:04,970 --> 00:20:05,971
Come on, boy.

284
00:20:06,013 --> 00:20:07,014
RADBURN: Up these stairs.

285
00:20:07,097 --> 00:20:09,308
BURCH: Get down out
of that wagon. Come on.

286
00:20:10,017 --> 00:20:11,310
Come on. Move it!

287
00:20:11,894 --> 00:20:13,187
Let's go!

288
00:20:13,270 --> 00:20:14,771
Up, up, up the stairs.

289
00:20:15,981 --> 00:20:17,399
Come on, let's go.

290
00:20:22,029 --> 00:20:23,405
Come on, move it!

291
00:20:23,864 --> 00:20:25,365
All right, come on.

292
00:20:27,242 --> 00:20:29,369
RADBURN: Hey, you. Get up.

293
00:20:29,870 --> 00:20:31,413
Sit down, right there.

294
00:20:31,872 --> 00:20:33,207
<i>(BURCH LAUGHING)</i>

295
00:20:34,041 --> 00:20:35,041
Come on.

296
00:20:36,543 --> 00:20:38,253
Right there. Just sit down.

297
00:21:14,540 --> 00:21:16,875
Cheer up and don't be so cast down.

298
00:21:22,214 --> 00:21:23,423
<i>(DOOR SLAMS)</i>

299
00:21:26,844 --> 00:21:31,140
If you want to survive,
do and say as little as possible.

300
00:21:32,391 --> 00:21:36,854
Tell no one who you really are
and tell no one you can read and write.

301
00:21:38,981 --> 00:21:41,942
Unless you want to be a dead nigger.

302
00:21:42,025 --> 00:21:43,318
<i>(DOOR OPENS)</i>

303
00:21:57,416 --> 00:21:59,084
MAN: Now keep your mouth shut.

304
00:22:06,842 --> 00:22:08,760
I say we fight.

305
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:11,180
The crew is fairly small.

306
00:22:11,963 --> 00:22:14,283
Were it well planned,
I believe they could be strong-armed.

307
00:22:14,308 --> 00:22:16,185
Three can't go against the whole crew.

308
00:22:17,311 --> 00:22:19,313
The rest here are niggers.

309
00:22:19,771 --> 00:22:21,064
Born and bred slaves.

310
00:22:21,190 --> 00:22:23,400
Niggers ain't got no stomach for a fight.

311
00:22:23,525 --> 00:22:25,027
Not a damn one.

312
00:22:25,194 --> 00:22:28,989
All's I know,
if we get where we're traveling...

313
00:22:29,323 --> 00:22:30,866
we'll wish we'd died trying.

314
00:22:30,991 --> 00:22:33,368
Survival's not about certain death,

315
00:22:33,452 --> 00:22:36,038
it's about keeping your head down.

316
00:22:39,041 --> 00:22:41,877
Days ago, I was with my family...

317
00:22:43,337 --> 00:22:45,172
in my home.

318
00:22:46,798 --> 00:22:49,009
Now you tell me all is lost.

319
00:22:51,178 --> 00:22:54,348
"Tell no one who I am."
That's the way to survive?

320
00:22:57,768 --> 00:22:59,770
Well, I don't want to survive.

321
00:23:01,230 --> 00:23:04,316
I want to live.

322
00:24:03,292 --> 00:24:04,543
<i>(LAUGHS)</i>

323
00:24:06,336 --> 00:24:07,546
<i>(STABS)</i>

324
00:24:14,094 --> 00:24:15,179
<i>(SCREAMING)</i>

325
00:24:33,113 --> 00:24:34,865
Better off.

326
00:24:35,824 --> 00:24:37,284
Better than us.

327
00:24:54,259 --> 00:24:55,511
I don't see him.

328
00:24:55,844 --> 00:24:56,844
Clemens!

329
00:24:56,970 --> 00:24:58,388
- Clemens Ray!
- Master.

330
00:24:58,514 --> 00:24:59,890
- Clemens!
- Master Ray, Sir!

331
00:25:00,015 --> 00:25:01,225
Master Ray!

332
00:25:01,350 --> 00:25:02,471
JONUS: Who's in charge here?

333
00:25:02,768 --> 00:25:03,769
I'm the captain!

334
00:25:03,852 --> 00:25:05,020
I'm Mr. Jonus Ray.

335
00:25:05,187 --> 00:25:06,855
My solicitor has
documentation...

336
00:25:06,980 --> 00:25:09,775
verifying the negro
known as Clemens Ray is my property.

337
00:25:09,858 --> 00:25:12,194
I know nothing of
this arrangement.

338
00:25:12,319 --> 00:25:14,120
JONUS: You are ordered to
return that property

339
00:25:14,196 --> 00:25:16,031
immediately or be
charged with thievery.

340
00:25:17,199 --> 00:25:18,367
Free him!

341
00:25:21,328 --> 00:25:22,412
Master.

342
00:25:22,538 --> 00:25:24,373
Master Ray, Sir.

343
00:25:25,916 --> 00:25:26,916
Clemens!

344
00:25:27,042 --> 00:25:28,168
- Clemens!
- CAPTAIN: Get him back!

345
00:25:28,293 --> 00:25:29,795
Clemens!

346
00:25:30,295 --> 00:25:31,338
Clemens!

347
00:25:32,256 --> 00:25:33,256
Clemens!

348
00:26:03,203 --> 00:26:05,080
<i>(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)</i>

349
00:26:37,863 --> 00:26:39,072
<i>(SINGING)</i>

350
00:26:39,364 --> 00:26:40,824
Mr. Parker.

351
00:26:40,866 --> 00:26:44,161
Ah, Mr. Northup. Mrs. Northup.

352
00:26:44,328 --> 00:26:46,371
Solomon, could I interest you
in a new cravat?

353
00:26:46,497 --> 00:26:47,831
Pure silk, by way of the French.

354
00:26:47,956 --> 00:26:50,501
We're in need of
a fresh carryall for my Mrs.'s travels.

355
00:26:50,834 --> 00:26:51,834
Nothing more.

356
00:26:51,835 --> 00:26:53,378
The year has passed already.

357
00:26:53,504 --> 00:26:54,880
Off to work at Sandy Hill again?

358
00:26:55,047 --> 00:26:56,047
I am.

359
00:26:56,048 --> 00:26:57,299
I have just the thing.

360
00:26:57,424 --> 00:26:59,176
Something to suit your style...

361
00:26:59,259 --> 00:27:01,845
and yet sturdy enough
for the 40-mile round trip.

362
00:27:01,970 --> 00:27:02,971
It's beautiful.

363
00:27:03,096 --> 00:27:04,096
At what price?

364
00:27:04,181 --> 00:27:05,181
We will take it.

365
00:27:05,224 --> 00:27:08,352
Children, come see what you
father has just purchased for me.

366
00:27:08,477 --> 00:27:10,062
Mr. Parker: One moment, Sir,
and you'll be assisted.

367
00:27:10,187 --> 00:27:11,980
- Mr. Parker.
- Sir?

368
00:27:12,105 --> 00:27:13,305
If we could discuss the price.

369
00:27:13,398 --> 00:27:15,108
Oh, forgive me, Solomon.
Forgive me, Mrs. Northup.

370
00:27:15,234 --> 00:27:17,277
A customer waits. Welcome, Sir.

371
00:27:17,402 --> 00:27:19,279
SOLOMON: Shop well, Sir,
but mind your wallet.

372
00:27:19,404 --> 00:27:21,198
Mr. Parker: Pay no attention
to this gentleman's nonsense.

373
00:27:21,365 --> 00:27:22,407
Jasper!

374
00:27:24,034 --> 00:27:25,869
My regrets for the intrusion, Sir.

375
00:27:26,161 --> 00:27:27,871
SOLOMON: No intrusion.

376
00:27:31,542 --> 00:27:33,126
Good day, Sir.

377
00:27:33,544 --> 00:27:34,878
Mr. Parker: Good day.

378
00:27:35,003 --> 00:27:36,547
Jasper, out.

379
00:27:44,447 --> 00:27:46,657
Very good. Very good.

380
00:27:46,949 --> 00:27:49,618
Let's see, here. Eliza!

381
00:27:50,870 --> 00:27:53,122
Stand up when you
hear your name. Eliza.

382
00:27:54,081 --> 00:27:55,081
Lethe!

383
00:27:58,461 --> 00:27:59,461
John.

384
00:28:00,796 --> 00:28:02,006
Oren.

385
00:28:03,424 --> 00:28:04,550
Platt.

386
00:28:07,470 --> 00:28:08,512
Platt.

387
00:28:11,640 --> 00:28:13,017
<i>(SIGHS)</i>Stand up.

388
00:28:15,019 --> 00:28:16,520
You fit the description given.

389
00:28:16,645 --> 00:28:18,006
Why didn't you answer when called?

390
00:28:18,063 --> 00:28:19,482
My name is not Platt.

391
00:28:19,648 --> 00:28:20,648
My name...

392
00:28:22,735 --> 00:28:24,445
Your name is Platt.

393
00:28:26,655 --> 00:28:28,783
Captain, get these niggers to my cart.

394
00:28:29,366 --> 00:28:31,118
<i>(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)</i>

395
00:28:41,545 --> 00:28:42,630
Mmm.

396
00:28:48,427 --> 00:28:49,512
<i>(CHUCKLES)</i>

397
00:28:50,888 --> 00:28:52,098
Move.

398
00:28:55,851 --> 00:28:57,611
FREEMAN: I believe I have
something very much

399
00:28:57,645 --> 00:28:59,105
to your liking in the back room.

400
00:28:59,438 --> 00:29:01,023
Follow me, please.

401
00:29:01,148 --> 00:29:03,984
Yes. Now, inspect them at your leisure...

402
00:29:04,110 --> 00:29:08,948
but I ask you to
pay particular regard to young Ezra here.

403
00:29:09,115 --> 00:29:10,491
Incredibly sound limbs.

404
00:29:10,616 --> 00:29:12,701
I have never seen anything
quite like him.

405
00:29:12,827 --> 00:29:15,746
And this marvelous creature.
Can you believe it? Mmm?

406
00:29:15,871 --> 00:29:17,581
She'll make a fine lady's maid.

407
00:29:17,706 --> 00:29:18,833
Madam?<i>(CHUCKLES)</i>

408
00:29:19,125 --> 00:29:20,876
So, inspect at your leisure.

409
00:29:21,001 --> 00:29:23,421
Take your time.
Help yourself to refreshments.

410
00:29:23,546 --> 00:29:26,549
Gentlemen, what catches
your fancy here? Hmm?

411
00:29:26,966 --> 00:29:27,967
This boy? Yes?

412
00:29:28,092 --> 00:29:30,428
Open your mouth. Open wider.

413
00:29:30,553 --> 00:29:32,888
Look in there.
Never been sick a day in his life.

414
00:29:33,013 --> 00:29:34,693
And I call particular attention to Martha.

415
00:29:34,765 --> 00:29:37,101
She is an excellent pastry cook.

416
00:29:37,435 --> 00:29:39,019
Ah, Mr. Ford.

417
00:29:39,562 --> 00:29:41,814
Splendid seeing you, Sir.
What catches your fancy?

418
00:29:41,939 --> 00:29:43,941
This lad? He's very brawny.

419
00:29:44,066 --> 00:29:46,861
How much for the ones Platt and Eliza?

420
00:29:46,944 --> 00:29:48,612
Ah, yes.

421
00:29:48,904 --> 00:29:51,031
A thousand for Platt. Uh... Oh.

422
00:29:51,115 --> 00:29:53,951
This is a nigger of
considerable talent, I assure you.

423
00:29:54,076 --> 00:29:55,828
700 for Eliza.

424
00:29:55,953 --> 00:29:57,747
My fairest price.

425
00:29:57,997 --> 00:29:59,123
Mmm.

426
00:29:59,957 --> 00:30:01,125
You will accept a note?

427
00:30:01,459 --> 00:30:03,919
Please, Sir. Do not divide my family.

428
00:30:04,044 --> 00:30:05,463
Do not take me unless you take my children.

429
00:30:05,629 --> 00:30:06,630
Eliza! Quiet!

430
00:30:06,756 --> 00:30:08,516
You will have the most
faithful slave in me.

431
00:30:08,632 --> 00:30:09,884
The most faithful slave
that has ever lived.

432
00:30:10,009 --> 00:30:11,135
But I beg that you do not separate us.

433
00:30:11,427 --> 00:30:12,470
Your price for the boy?

434
00:30:12,636 --> 00:30:13,846
Eliza! Stop it!

435
00:30:13,971 --> 00:30:15,139
I will give you something to cry about.

436
00:30:15,473 --> 00:30:17,641
Randall, come forward. Come, come, come.

437
00:30:17,767 --> 00:30:19,894
Now, do you see how fit this boy is?

438
00:30:20,019 --> 00:30:21,437
Like ripe fruit.

439
00:30:21,562 --> 00:30:24,482
May I take your stick a moment?
Observe this.

440
00:30:24,607 --> 00:30:26,567
Randall, jump, jump, jump. Run, run, run.

441
00:30:26,692 --> 00:30:28,861
Very good! Higher.

442
00:30:28,986 --> 00:30:30,071
Now, you see this.

443
00:30:30,404 --> 00:30:33,866
It's very likely
he will grow into a fine beast.

444
00:30:35,076 --> 00:30:36,827
600 for the boy.

445
00:30:36,952 --> 00:30:38,621
Fair and final.

446
00:30:39,080 --> 00:30:40,456
Done.

447
00:30:40,581 --> 00:30:42,875
Superb. A moment, please.

448
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:44,418
Mr. Ford.

449
00:30:44,627 --> 00:30:45,711
- Please.
- Eliza!

450
00:30:45,878 --> 00:30:47,630
How much for the little girl?

451
00:30:47,713 --> 00:30:48,798
Ah...

452
00:30:49,131 --> 00:30:50,466
You have no use for her.

453
00:30:50,591 --> 00:30:52,134
One so young will bring you no profit.

454
00:30:52,468 --> 00:30:54,386
No, no, no. I cannot sell the girl.

455
00:30:54,512 --> 00:30:58,015
No, there's heaps
and piles of money to be made from her.

456
00:30:58,140 --> 00:31:00,601
She's a beauty. One of the regular bloods.

457
00:31:00,726 --> 00:31:03,526
None of your thick-lipped, bullet-heated,
cotton-picking niggers, here.

458
00:31:03,646 --> 00:31:06,398
Her child, man.

459
00:31:06,583 --> 00:31:07,583
Please.

460
00:31:07,608 --> 00:31:09,688
For God's sake,
are you not sentimental in the least?

461
00:31:09,693 --> 00:31:12,446
My sentimentality extends
the length of a coin.

462
00:31:12,613 --> 00:31:13,989
God, please.

463
00:31:14,657 --> 00:31:17,952
Now do you take this lot, Mr. Ford,
or do you pass on them?

464
00:31:18,119 --> 00:31:21,789
Please, please. Please.

465
00:31:21,872 --> 00:31:23,541
I will take the ones Platt and Eliza.

466
00:31:23,666 --> 00:31:24,667
Sold, Eliza and Platt.

467
00:31:24,792 --> 00:31:25,876
I will not go without my children!

468
00:31:26,001 --> 00:31:27,086
Goddamn sniveling wench!

469
00:31:27,364 --> 00:31:28,604
You will not take them from me!

470
00:31:28,629 --> 00:31:29,880
God damn you! Get her out of here, Cape!

471
00:31:29,964 --> 00:31:31,424
<i>(CHILDREN SCREAMING)</i>

472
00:31:31,549 --> 00:31:33,134
Please! No! No!

473
00:31:33,467 --> 00:31:34,969
Get her out of here, God damn it!

474
00:31:35,094 --> 00:31:38,055
Platt, get your fiddle.
Play, play, play something.

475
00:31:38,389 --> 00:31:41,475
I will give you something to cry
about, you goddamned witch!

476
00:31:41,600 --> 00:31:43,727
Get her out of here, Cape! Out, now!

477
00:31:43,936 --> 00:31:45,646
<i>(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)</i>

478
00:31:45,729 --> 00:31:47,440
CHILDREN: Mama! Mama! Mama!

479
00:31:48,149 --> 00:31:50,109
Yes.

480
00:31:50,443 --> 00:31:53,028
Mr. Ford, a pleasure.

481
00:31:53,446 --> 00:31:54,989
<i>(CHILDREN CONTINUE SCREAMING)</i>

482
00:32:09,754 --> 00:32:11,964
Did you bring all those niggers?

483
00:32:12,089 --> 00:32:14,467
Two of them? You got two?

484
00:32:14,568 --> 00:32:15,568
FORD: Mr. Chapin.

485
00:32:15,593 --> 00:32:16,593
<i>(SOBBING)</i>

486
00:32:16,802 --> 00:32:19,138
MISTRESS FORD: This one's crying.
Why is this one crying?

487
00:32:19,472 --> 00:32:20,973
FORD: Separated from her children.

488
00:32:21,098 --> 00:32:22,641
- Oh, dear.
- It couldn't be helped.

489
00:32:22,808 --> 00:32:23,976
Poor, poor woman.

490
00:32:24,101 --> 00:32:25,478
- Mr. Chapin.
- Yes, Sir.

491
00:32:25,644 --> 00:32:27,084
Tomorrow, you have to take these two

492
00:32:27,146 --> 00:32:28,689
up to the mill and start them working.

493
00:32:28,814 --> 00:32:30,024
For now, make them adequate.

494
00:32:30,149 --> 00:32:31,950
Fix them a meal
and have them rest themselves.

495
00:32:32,068 --> 00:32:33,444
Yes, Sir.

496
00:32:34,361 --> 00:32:35,488
Come on, now.

497
00:32:35,946 --> 00:32:38,115
Come on! Don't dawdle!

498
00:32:38,491 --> 00:32:40,993
Something to eat, and some rest.

499
00:32:41,368 --> 00:32:42,848
Your children will soon be forgotten.

500
00:33:10,147 --> 00:33:12,400
For all of you raw niggers
that don't know...

501
00:33:12,525 --> 00:33:16,821
my name is John Tibeats,
William Ford's Chief carpenter.

502
00:33:16,946 --> 00:33:20,449
You will refer to me as "Master."

503
00:33:20,616 --> 00:33:24,370
Mr. Chapin is the overseer
on this plantation.

504
00:33:24,495 --> 00:33:28,958
You, too, will refer to him as "Master."

505
00:33:30,042 --> 00:33:31,961
So, clap your hands.

506
00:33:35,631 --> 00:33:38,384
Like this. Come on.

507
00:33:39,051 --> 00:33:41,470
Come on, now. Clap your hands.

508
00:33:45,558 --> 00:33:47,810
<i>(SINGING)</i>Nigger run
Nigger flew.

509
00:33:47,977 --> 00:33:50,479
<i>Nigger tore his shirt in two.</i>

510
00:33:50,604 --> 00:33:52,857
<i>Run, run
The pattyroller will get you.</i>

511
00:33:52,982 --> 00:33:55,067
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away.</i>

512
00:33:59,697 --> 00:34:01,615
TIBEATS: <i>That's right.
Like you mean it.</i>

513
00:34:02,616 --> 00:34:04,785
<i>(SINGING)</i>Nigger run
Run so fast.

514
00:34:04,869 --> 00:34:07,371
<i>Stove his head in a hornet's nest.</i>

515
00:34:07,455 --> 00:34:09,457
<i>Run, run
The pattyroller will get you.</i>

516
00:34:09,623 --> 00:34:12,626
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away.</i>

517
00:34:13,419 --> 00:34:15,629
<i>Run, nigger, run
The pattyroller will get you.</i>

518
00:34:15,796 --> 00:34:17,923
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away.</i>

519
00:34:19,925 --> 00:34:21,969
<i>Some folk say a nigger don't steal.</i>

